# Overview

 The Missoula Pro am is a uniquely formatted timbersports cmpetition. It contain's 2 days of competition: A college competition on Day 1 (Friday) and a professional competition on Day 2 (Saturday). T The formats for the pro show and tghe college show are different. I will detail them below. 

# College Competition:

## Format
* "Teams" are organized by school and can have up to 8 total competitors on them. They MUST have a minimum of 2 competitors per gender. Schools can send as many teams as they want. 

    * For example, Universtiy of Montana could send UM-A (6 Males, 2 Females), UM-B (4 Males, 4 Females), and UM-C (3 Males, 2 Females). Colorado State University could send CSU-A (2 males, 6 Females), CSU-B (5 males, 3 Females), and CSU-C (4 males, 4 females). 

* The events will attempt to run in a solid batch of heats, with some deliberate exceptions. For instance, you should run all of men's single buck and then all of women's singlebuck.

## Gendered Segregation
* Men's and women's events are run separately, meaning that there will need to be a men's heat and women's heat for each event (For example, we will need to build a Men's Underhand Hard Hit and a Women's underhand Hard Hit).

## Partnered Events
Partnered events require two competitors from the same team to compete. These pairs are NOT randomly assigned, they are deliberately assigned during the entry process
The exception to the gender segregation rule applies to the following partnered events: 
    
        Pulp Toss
        Peavey Log Roll
        Jack & Jill Sawing

In any of these events, one man and one woman will compete with eachother in a team. Though Double Buck is a gender segregated event, it is still a partnered event and will require either 2 men or 2 women 

## Scoring

* The College competitions are formatted and scored to be both an individual and team event. 

* Individual scores are tracked throughout the day and are based off of placing. The following schema is used to assign points: 1st Place: 10 points, 2nd PLace: 7 Points, 3rd Place: 5 points, 4th Place: 3 points, 5th place: 2 points, 6th place, 1 point.

* Individual scores are also combined to form Team scores. For instance, If Bill from UM-A has 24 points, Sally from UM-B has 31 points, Steve From UM-A has 11 points, Mary from UM-B has 19 points, and Susan from UM-C has 9 points, then the team totals would be UM-A: 35 points, UM-B: 50 points, UM-C: 9 points. 

* College competitions have events that can be measured by time, points, distance, or number of hits. For the events that are reliant on time, the lowest time will be scored the highest. For Events that are scored by points, the highest amount of points will be scored the highest. For events that are scored in distance, the greatest distance will be scored the highest. For events that are scored by the number of hits (all events designated as a Hard Hit), the fewest number of hits gets scored the highest.

    ### Bull/Belle and Overall Team
    * At the end of both days of competition, we will need a tabulation of the top 5 College Teams, as well as the top 5 individual Men and the top 5 individual women. The top overall man is designated as "Bull of the Woods" and the top overall woman is designated as the "Belle of the Woods" 
* At the end of both days, in addition to the overall and team scores, there will need to be a printout of the results of every single event.

## Events Lists

* College Events also differ from pro events in that there are OPEN and CLOSED events. 

    * OPEN events are events that all competitors are signed up for. They are run at the beginning of the day and sometimes through the competition as needed. There is no set heat list, competitors come and go as their schedule allows. IMPORTANT NOTE: In recent years to save time and resources, the Missoula Pro Am has listed traditionally OPEN events as CLOSED (counts against Atheletes' 6 events). When we build the tournament from the beginning, I want the option to designate this specific set of events as *either* OPEN  or CLOSED. 

    ### THE FOLLOWING EVENTS ARE DESIGNATED AS OPEN EVENTS AT THE MISSOULA PRO-AM

        Axe Throw (score)
        Peavy Log Roll (time)
        Caber Toss (distance)
        Pulp Toss (time)


    * CLOSED events are events are ones that the athletes sign up for specifically. Athletes are allowed to sign up for a maximum of 6 events.

    ### THE FOLLOWING EVENTS ARE DESIGNATED AS CLOSED EVENTS AT THE MISSOULA PRO-AM

        Underhand Hard Hit (number of hits)
        Underhand Speed (time)
        Standing Block Hard Hit (number of hits)
        Standing Block Speed (time)
        Single Buck (time)
        Double Buck (time)
        Jack & Jill Sawing (time)
        Stock Saw (time)
        Speed Climb (time)
        Obstacle Pole (time)
        Chokerman's Race (time)
        Birling (bracket)
        1-Board Spring Board

## Special Rules for events

* Chokerman's Race, Obstacle Pole, and Climb will require 2x runs built into the schedule. For each of these events, you are running head-to-head against another opponent on a nearly similar course. A second run helps eliminate bias or an unfair advantage that one course has over the other. In these timed events, the fastest of these two times is used to score the event. For each of these events, the course will be defined as the following:

        Obstacle Pole: Pole 1/ Pole 2
        Chokerman's Race: Course 1/ Course 2
        Speed Climb: Pole 2/ Pole 4

* Birling will be held at the very end of the day. The Birling Bracket will be double elimination to determine a winner out to 6th. The bracket will be pre-seeded and designed prior to the competition's start
    
# "Friday Night Feature"
* The Friday Night Feature is run whenever there is either a set of special events, or there needs to be spillover due to scheduling. When we are designing the schedule, we will build this separately. If events are held on a Friday night, the following events are typically held: 

        Collegiate 1-Board
        Pro 1- Board 
        Pro 3- Board Jigger.  

# Professional Competition

## Format
* Unlike the college format where events are run one heat at a time and sequentially, the Profesisonal show runs on a "Flight" system, where a heat from each event is worked in to give the crowd a variety of events to watch at a fast pace. 

    For example, Flight 1 might look like the following:
    Springboard Heat 1
    Women's Single Buck Heat 1
    Men's Underhand Heat 1
    Cookie Stack Heat 1
    etc., etc., 

* The flights don't neccessarily have to have ONLY one heat from each event in the flight, but it does help with the crowd engagement to keep a wide variety. A good exampe of this would be to have a heat of the underhand, followed by 2 or 3 heats of the Obstacle Pole (it is a fast paced event that is a crowd pleaser and also has only two competitors at a time, so there will naturally be a lot of heats)

* It is important to group compettors by ability group ESPECIALLY IN THE SPRINGBOARD. If there are 4 competitors that cut 4+ minute sprigboards, it is helpful to put them all in the same heat to keep there from being 4x 4-minute Springboard heats.


## Gendered Segregation
* Men's and women's events are run separately, meaning that there will need to be a men's heat and women's heat for each event (For example, we will need to build a Men's Underhand and a Women's underhand).

* The exception will be the following events:
        
        Jack & Jill Sawing
        Birling (NOT GENDER SEGREGATED LIKE COLLEGE!)
        Pro 1-Board Springboard
        Obstacle Pole
        Cookie Stack

## Partnered Events
Partnered events require two competitors from to compete. These pairs are NOT randomly assigned, they are deliberately assigned during the entry process. The following events will be partnered events:

    Double Buck 
    Partnered Axe Throw
    Jack & Jill Sawing

During registration, if a partner is not explicitly listed on the form, I want a way for the system to auto-assign a partner.

## Scoring

* There is no show-wide tracking of points for pro competitors, but payouts need to be tracked. Payouts will vary by dollar amount and the placing that it will pay out to for every event and will be distributed at the end of the show.

* At the end of both days there will need to be a printout of the results of every single event.

* An example of the current college Scoring format is included in the project files: 

