## Events Lists

The Following Events may be hosted at the Missoula Pro-Am's Pro show:

    Springboard (time)
    Pro 1-Board (time)
    3- Baord Jigger (time)
    Underhand (time)
    Standing Block (time)
    Stock Saw (time)
    Hot Saw (time)
    Single Buck (time)
    Double Buck (time)
    Jack & Jill (time)
    Partnered Axe Throw (score)
    Obstacle Pole (time)
    Cookie Stack (time)
    Pole Climb (time)

This is not a definitive list, as events will be selected based on wood availability each year during the show design phase. It is also important to note that there is NOT a requirement to host both a men's and women's version of each event. (For example, many times the Pro Am will host the women's standing block, but not the men's standing block)

## Special Rules for events

* There are 4 dummies for springboard and each dummy can be used 3 times for each event. Left handed springbaord cutters need to be identified during the signup and assigned to the same dummy (spread out throughout the heats/flights). Wood calculations need to account for the amount of dummies needed.

* Birling will always be done as the last event of the pro show

* The pro Obstacle Pole will only be allotted ONE run

* Both Cookie Stack and Standing block will use the same stands! 

* All hand-sawing events (Single Buck, Double Buck, Jack & Jill) use the same 8 stands. Though there are 8 saw stands, they are grouped in sets of 4. One heat of sawing (4 stands) will go while the other heat (other 4 stands) sets in.

* All power-sawing events (stock saw and hot saw) will be executed on saw stands 1-4. Stock Saw (both pro and collegiate) will be held on stands 1 & 2

* Partnered Axe throw will be split into two parts: pre show preliminaries and the finals held during the show. All teams will throw off prior to the show, and the top 4 teams will throw at some point during the show. One team will throw off at some point during each flight. This means there needs to be a way to easily ammend the schedule with the teams that made the finals.


## College Event Integration

### College Events held on Satruday

* In the interest of time, some college events will need to be rolled to Saturday. They will be judged and scored like college events. The second run of the Chokerman's Race will absolutely need to be conducted Saturday. Depending on availability, the following are acceptable events from the college leagues that can be worked into the Saturday schedule if absolutely neccessary (their order reflects order of preference):

1. Men's Standing Block Speed
2. Men's Standing Block Hard Hit
3. Women's Standing Block Speed
4. Women's Standing Block Hard Hit
5. Men's Obstacle Pole

### "Pro-AM" Relay

One of the main purposes of the Missoula Pro Am is to create an enviornment that breaks down the divide between the college athletes and professional athletes. One of the the best ways we do this is with a "Pro-Am" relay. Two teams of will be randomly drawn prior to the start of the show. Each team will consist of 6 competitors: 3 college competitors, and 3 professional competitors. The teams will arrange themselves however they see fit to complete the following 3 events: partnered sawing (can be arranged with any combination ) sawing, Standing Butcher Block, Underhand Butcher Block.

This relay will need to be fit into one of the flights.

Both Professional Competitors will indicate their desire to be drawn into the Pro-Am relay on their entry forms.

NOTE: The results of this relay do not count towards team or individual college scores. This is also the ONLY event where the college competitors will be capable of winning money.


# Stand Allocation For Show (College and Pro)

    Springboard: 4 Stands
    Underhand: 5 Stands (could change )
    Obstacle Pole: 2 Sides (Pole 1/ Pole 2)
    Speed Climb: 2 poles (Pole 2, Pole 4)
    Standing Block: 5 stands
    Cookie Stack: 5 Stands
    Stock Saw: 2 Stands
    Hot Saw: 4 stands
    Single buck: 8 Stands
    Double Buck: 8 Stands
    Jack & Jill: 8 Stands
    Partnered Axe Throw: 1 target for finals

# Show Entry


## Professional Entries 
* Professional entries are done individually. At theend we can develop the most optimized entry form for the system.

* Professional entries will have entry fees. The enry fees will be by-event, and the price will vary with each event

* Professional entry form needs to ask whether they are a current American Lumberjack Assosciation (ALA) Member. There needs to be an option in the menu to check whether a memeber has self-reported current membership.

* Professional competitors will also indicate whether they are interested in entering the Pro-Am lottery when they register

* In addition to Events entered, we need to track a competitor's name, gender, address, phone number, email address, and shirt size (if show is providing shirts)

* The show may elect whether or not they are sneding shirts or not. This will be determined prior to the sending out of the entry forms.

* There needs to be an option to indicate whether or not you are sharing gear with another compeitor and what events you will be sharing the equipment. Some competitors share expensive gear or gear that is difficult to travel with like Springboards, hotsaws, or single saws. This is to prevent two competitors that are sharing from being put in the same heat.


